BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:evt-2026-041@osweekplus.nyc
SUMMARY:A DPI Approach to Next Generation Trade and Transport
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T130000
DESCRIPTION:This session will explore how Digital Public Infrastructure (DPI) and open‑source Digital Public Goods are transforming international trade and transport. Organized by UNECE’s Transport Division in partnership with UN OHRLLS, the Czech Republic Customs, and the International Road Transport Union (IRU), the panel will highlight practical, interoperable, and legally grounded digital solutions supporting cross‑border operations. The discussion will focus on ongoing efforts to digitalize key United \nRSVP: https://www.unopensource.org/agenda
LOCATION:New York, NY
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:evt-2026-042@osweekplus.nyc
SUMMARY:Advancing Population-Scale Innovation with Safe & Inclusive DPI (1)
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T130000
DESCRIPTION:Countries are rapidly adopting digital public infrastructure (digital ID, payments, data exchange) to deliver services at population scale. But as DPI scales, so do the risks: exclusion of marginalized populations, security vulnerabilities, privacy failures, and vendor lock-in, among others. Despite growing consensus that safeguards are essential, most implementers lack practical guidance on what safeguards look like in practice and how to operationalize them alongside design and rollout.The UN \nRSVP: https://www.unopensource.org/agenda
LOCATION:New York, NY
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:evt-2026-043@osweekplus.nyc
SUMMARY:Building Inclusion: Identity, Payments, and the Real Cost of Digital Public Infrastructure
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T130000
DESCRIPTION:From Venezuelan migrants navigating Colombia’s Bre-B payment system, to Ethiopia’s rollout of Fayda ID, to the global push for digital public infrastructure, this session examines a critical question: when does digital public infrastructure actually expand inclusion, and when does it reinforce barriers? By connecting real-world frictions in remittances, the evolving role of digital identity and how it can leverage and build on open-source systems, and the financial and governance trade-offs of D\nRSVP: https://www.unopensource.org/agenda
LOCATION:New York, NY
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:evt-2026-044@osweekplus.nyc
SUMMARY:DPI Sustainability for Health, Learning and Science
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260624T130000
DESCRIPTION:As learning, health and scientific systems grow increasingly digital, the governance of digital commons and open infrastructure has become both an urgent public interest challenge and a strategic opportunity. This session explores these issues, including through a UNESCO Panel on Open Solutions and WHO/UNICC panel on Health DPI, which will highlight how Digital Public Infrastructure (DPI) and digital public goods—including open repositories, Open Access, and Open Educational Resources—can enable\nRSVP: https://www.unopensource.org/agenda
LOCATION:New York, NY
END:VEVENT
